        {
            "heading": "Noah as Herald of Righteousness — The Prophetic Witness (65:12-13)",
            "body": "<strong>Noah's Dual Role:</strong> [A] Second Peter 2:5 calls Noah a 'herald of righteousness' (kēryx dikaiosynēs), indicating he did not merely build an ark but proclaimed God's coming judgment. [B] Hebrews 11:7 states, 'By faith Noah, being warned by God concerning events as yet unseen, in reverent fear constructed an ark for the saving of his household. By this he condemned the world and became an heir of the righteousness that comes by faith.' The ark construction itself was a 120-year prophetic sign (Genesis 6:3) — a visible, tangible warning that judgment was coming. Every hammer blow declared, 'Repent, for the flood is near.'<br><br><strong>The Prophetic Pattern:</strong> [B] Noah embodies the prophetic calling: (1) Receive divine revelation, (2) Proclaim it faithfully regardless of response, (3) Suffer ridicule and rejection, (4) Be vindicated when the word comes to pass. This is Jeremiah's experience (Jeremiah 20:7-18), Ezekiel's (Ezekiel 3:4-11), and ultimately Christ's (John 1:11, 'He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him'). [C] First Enoch 65 positions Noah within this tradition — he receives revelation from Enoch, understands the signs, and (by implication) warns his generation. The text does not record the warning explicitly, but 2 Peter assumes it.<br><br><strong>The Righteousness Requirement:</strong> [A] Genesis 6:9 declares, 'Noah was a righteous man, blameless in his generation. Noah walked with God.' The Hebrew <em>tsaddiq</em> (righteous) and <em>tamim</em> (blameless/complete) indicate covenant faithfulness — Noah maintained right relationship with God in a corrupted world. [B] This is not sinless perfection but covenant loyalty. He is the anti-type to his generation: they were corrupt and violent (Genesis 6:11-12), he was righteous and blameless. [C] Ezekiel 14:14, 20 lists Noah alongside Daniel and Job as exemplars of righteousness whose intercession could save only themselves in a time of judgment. The principle: individual righteousness matters, but it cannot indefinitely forestall corporate judgment. Noah's righteousness saved his household (8 people) but did not prevent the flood. The pattern recurs: Lot's righteousness saved his immediate family but not Sodom (Genesis 19). [B] This underscores the seriousness of corporate sin and the limits of vicarious righteousness — a theme Jesus addresses in Luke 13:1-5 ('unless you repent, you will all likewise perish')."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Theological Synthesis — Cosmic Order, Moral Order, and Divine Justice",
            "body": "<strong>The Integrated Worldview:</strong> [B] First Enoch 65 operates within a worldview where physical cosmos, moral order, and spiritual realm are interconnected. Sin is not merely a legal infraction but a cosmic disruption. When the Watchers transgressed, they did not just break a rule — they violated the boundary between heaven and earth, introducing chaos into the created order. [A] This is why Genesis 6:11-12 uses <em>shachat</em> (corrupt/destroy/ruin) three times in two verses — the same word describes both moral corruption and physical destruction. The earth itself is <em>ruined</em> by sin. Paul echoes this in Romans 8:20-21: 'the creation was subjected to futility' and is in 'bondage to corruption,' awaiting liberation.<br><br><strong>Divine Justice as Restoration:</strong> [B] The flood is not arbitrary divine wrath but <em>restorative justice</em>. A corrupted system must be purged for a new, righteous order to emerge. This is why the flood narrative ends with covenant (Genesis 9:8-17) — God commits to preserving the created order despite ongoing human sin ('I will never again curse the ground because of man, for the intention of man's heart is evil from his youth,' Genesis 8:21). [B] The rainbow becomes the sign of this covenant, a visible reminder that God will not again use water to destroy the earth. But 2 Peter 3:7 clarifies: the <em>mode</em> of judgment changes (fire instead of water), but judgment itself remains. The moral order demands it.<br><br><strong>Application to the Present:</strong> [C] First Enoch 65's cosmic disturbances function as a perpetual warning: the earth remains under the shadow of judgment until the final restoration. Every earthquake, every 'sign in the heavens,' every manifestation of disorder echoes Noah's alarm and calls the righteous to vigilance. [B] Jesus' command in Luke 21:28 applies: 'Now when these things begin to take place, straighten up and raise your heads, because your redemption is drawing near.' The signs are not cause for despair but for hope — they indicate that God's justice is on the move, that the current corrupt order will not stand forever, and that the righteous will be vindicated. [A] As Habakkuk 2:14 promises, 'For the earth will be filled with the knowledge of the glory of the LORD as the waters cover the sea.' The flood destroyed; the final judgment will cleanse and renew. Noah's ark saved 8; the New Jerusalem will house multitudes beyond number (Revelation 7:9). The pattern is judgment → remnant → restoration → glory."
